<font color="#FF0000">AMERASIANS, WHOSE FAULT?</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun  9  0:00:06 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Interesting replies. But gentlemen, allow me one correction. VietSon did not raise the issue of Amerasians, my wife did. She is not web wise, so she dictated and I typed.  She is a &quot;veteran&quot; child abuse social worker (25 years) and is tuned in to all forms of child abuse. Taught me alot.  She raised this issue, and it seems that it came as a surprise to many of you, and me. After that, VietSon mentioned that his wife too, was Amerasian (check the record if you doubt).  Point it that credit goes where credit goes, and I for one, stood in the kitchen with my mouth hanging open, when my wife asked me about this topic and I had no answer for her. Or why none of us had raised this issue before.<br><br>
I think instant immigration is probably a generation too late, unfortunately, for the victims.  The Amerasian babies, kids, and subsequent teenagers and now adults have been outcasts from the society (Viet Nam)  since the end of the war.  I don't know what we can do about that now.  All soldiers, American, Russian, German,  etc., tend to &quot;drop their seed&quot; along the way, and Viet Nam was no exception.  In Europe, the babies blended in, being white fathers and mothers. In Korea they clearly did not.  Nor did they in Occupied Japan. Viet Nam, same story.  Bosnians raping Croat Muslims, same story.<br><br>
Perhaps the most telling of this issue is that a woman, who happens to be a child abuse expert (i.e. increased awareness), raised the issue. Not VietSon, not any veteran, not any protestor. None of us, not even me. <br><br>
Gerald, your comments are noble, and I don't doubt them for a moment. Arthur, your research and recognization of the problem is intense. John, your &quot;cause&quot; may well be here. Joe, your idea's are good, but I wonder if they can be done.  <br><br>
Perhaps the real question here, and throughout history, is the real &quot;fruits of war&quot;, that soldiers (men) will do what men do, and women will do what women do, and as in all other wars, there will be oppspring.  Is it too late for them?  Why did the Vietnamese culture so reject these mixed race kids? Were there French-Vietnamese offspring and how were they treated? Perhaps not all the blame rests on the Americans, for a change.<br><br>
I think the question has eluded us ALL for so long, because we are all men, regardless of race, and war (and rape) and prostitution, as well as love affairs, have always been a part of the stage that war gets played on.  And when the play is over, the audience applauded and quietly left.  Only this time, it ain't being so quiet and it is asking WHY?
